  <h3><a href="https://queue.acm.org/listing.cfm?typefilter=Kodevicious&amp;sort=publication_date&amp;order=desc&amp;qc_type=Kodevicious&amp;article_type=&amp;item_topic=all&amp;filter_type=topic&amp;page_title=Kode%20Vicious&amp;filter=all">Kode Vicious</a> - <a href="https://queue.acm.org/listing.cfm?item_topic=AI&amp;qc_type=theme_list&amp;filter=AI&amp;page_title=AI&amp;order=desc">AI</a></h3> 
  <h1 class="hidetitle">KV the Apostate</h1> 
  <h2>Faith-based computing versus the unnatural science</h2> 
  <h3>George Neville-Neil</h3> 
  <p><b>Whether we ask an LLM or a recent graduate to type the code is less important than knowing what the code does, how it was built, and when to look under the hood.</b></p> 
  <p>Dear KV,</p> 
  <p>The hype cycle that is “AI” seems as if it will never end. What I was doing as a developer two years ago seems very different to what I’m doing now that management has required us to use LLMs in our work. Some of what these things do seems helpful—roughing out a general framework or helping with tasks such as creating unit tests that have often seemed like drudgery. From your writings, I suspect you remain skeptical and continue to be part of the old school that thinks this is a fad that will blow over. But do you believe there is something valuable in this current cycle? Or are you still typing out your programs one key press at a time?</p> 
  <p align="right" style="text-align:right">Button Pusher</p> 
  <p>Dear Button,</p> 
  <p>KV got into computing for a few reasons, one of which was to build and live in the future. So, while he definitely has strong beliefs about how best to do things, ignoring new tools and being part of the old guard are not in my nature. What is in KV’s nature, other than a propensity for outbursts of profanity, is a healthy dose of skepticism—a skepticism that has kept KV from ever completely joining any crowd. After all, the problem with joining a group is that, eventually, they have little hats, uniforms, and lists of people they want to wake up at three in the morning.</p> 
  <p>Let’s get down to the phrase that stands out to me most in your letter: “But do you believe...?” KV no more believes in AI than he believes in the Tooth Fairy, Santa Claus, or the Flying Spaghetti Monster. Belief is not a part of science or engineering, and anyone who says otherwise is building the next Leaning Tower of Pisa, the sole remnant of a series of failed towers. All the others fell because insufficient science and engineering went into their planning and execution.</p> 
  <p>Unfortunately, this word <i>belief</i> gets tossed around a lot in relation to the current LLM fad. The other day, in a discussion with a colleague, an admitted fanboy and cheerleader for the use of LLMs, I was pointed to a brief note (<a href="https://cs.stanford.edu/~knuth/papers/claude-cycles.pdf">https://cs.stanford.edu/~knuth/papers/claude-cycles.pdf</a>) written by one of the deepest of algorithmic thinkers and told, “See, even he is now a believer!” But, if you take the time to read what was written, you find there is nothing having to do with belief. Instead, it is a short, rigorous study of how this tool could be applied to a problem and how the people involved had managed to apply the tool and their intelligence to solve a problem they had been working on.</p> 
  <p>Did the tool help them solve the problem more quickly? Perhaps. Did the tool solve the problem for them? No, they solved the problem with the help of a new tool, just as humans have done since the first cave dweller picked up a femur bone and used it as a weapon—although that may have been under the influence of a large black obelisk that was making a crazy humming noise nearby.</p> 
  <p>When I pointed out the fallacy of using the term <i>belief</i> for anything science based, my colleague quoted the old saw about how “Computing added the word science to its name even though it’s not a science.” I pointed out, none too politely, that this was bullshit.</p> 
  <p>The crux of the matter is that the study of computing is, in fact, an unnatural science. It is the study of objects manufactured by humans, but which we now claim (or at least the LLM folks claim) are too complex to understand. Physics is the study of the natural world, and chemistry is applied physics with smoke and bangs, while biology is the study of naturally occurring living organisms. Those are properly called natural sciences. Which is to say I just added <i>science</i> to their names as well.</p> 
  <p>Whether or not we affix <i>science</i> to a name is immaterial. It is how we study what we study and whether we can apply the scientific method to derive reproducible results. If each time we do something we get a random but useful result, that’s still not science but merely luck. And, as someone who flies a lot, I prefer not to rely solely on luck in my flight controls, flaps, engines, or brakes.</p> 
  <p>Programming isn’t just typing the characters, any more than writing is. Or, as Truman Capote put it, “That’s not writing, that’s just typing!” Programming or software development—or whatever term you wish to use—is the application of thought to the creation of structures to be used in an abstract machine made real by silicon relays. The key here is the thought.</p> 
  <p>These new tools may indeed remove drudgery from our lives, although—like all new tools—they will surely replace that with other drudgery. The present moment reminds me of how architects, given a new material—concrete—went crazy using it in everything to create unlivable and unusable buildings that were so hideous they needed a new award, for neobrutalist architecture, to recognize these monstrosities.</p> 
  <p>The trend of architects building things “just because they could” has no more iconic and ironic expression than the CSAIL (Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory) building at MIT. The structure is so poorly laid out that no one can find their way through its twisted corridors without GPS, and it’s so poorly constructed that it leaks. MIT sued the architect once the building was complete. Similarly, if we use LLMs poorly—as so many people already are—we will generate megabytes of utter crap (aka AI slop, already the bane of many open source projects).</p> 
  <p>What we as software developers and designers need to do is to understand these tools and how to apply them. Whether we ask an LLM or a recent graduate to type the code is less important than knowing what the code does, how it was built, and when to look under the hood. Right now, everyone ought to be in coveralls with their hands covered in grease, or they’re going to find when they next hit the brakes that they’re likely to go sailing through the next red light.</p> 
  <p>Once the hype cycle ends, we will know what we know about LLMs and AI, but, at the moment, there is too much money and too much “belief” to form a clear picture. Always try the new tools, always be skeptical, and check your return values.</p> 
  <p align="right" style="text-align:right">KV</p> 
